<h2 id="parsing-linear-transformation">Parsing Linear Transformation</h2>

<p>Transformation: A function that takes in an input vector and <em>moves</em> it.
Linear: The <em>movement</em> described above is linear if and only if</p>

<ol>
  <li>the origin remains</li>
  <li>lines stay as lines. (In other words, the set of vectors that have the same span remains the same after the transformation)</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="geometric-intuition-of-linear-transformation-in-matrix-multiplication">Geometric intuition of Linear Transformation in Matrix Multiplication</h2>

<p>Recall the matrix multiplication operation</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">% <![CDATA[
T(\overrightarrow{v}) :=
\begin{bmatrix}
i_1 & j_1 \\
i_2 & j_2
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
v_1 \\
v_2
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
i_1 \\
i_2
\end{bmatrix} v_1
+
\begin{bmatrix}
j_1 \\
j_2
\end{bmatrix} v_2
=
\begin{bmatrix}
i_1v_1 & j_1v_2 \\
i_2v_1 & j_2v_2
\end{bmatrix} %]]></script>

<p>This <em>linear transformation</em> moves $ \overrightarrow{v} $ from the representation of the basis vectors in the coefficient matrix, ($ \overrightarrow{i} $, $ \overrightarrow{j} $)
to the standard basis. ($ \overrightarrow{e_x} = (1,0) $, $\overrightarrow{e_y} = (0, 1) $ in $ R_2 $.)
More crudely, the linear transformation of $ \overrightarrow{v} \ shows us what $ \overrightarrow{v} $ in the “world” represented by the basis vectors in the coefficient matrix, looks like in our “world”.</p>
